{"candidates": [{"content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency iff base candidate error e falls in the fragility window 1/(k+1) < e < k/(k+2) and critic precision p satisfies p > (1-r) * F_broke / (r * F_fixed), where F_broke/F_fixed is the ratio of broken-to-fixed majority cases; the mechanism is vote-margin-dependent filtering utility: when margins are thin, removing even one incorrect vote can flip the outcome (high utility), but when margins are wide (e near 0 or near 1), filtering has no flips available and false positives only erode correct majorities (net harm or zero).\", \"mechanism\": \"Let m = floor(k/2)+1 be the majority threshold. A 'fragile correct' majority has exactly m correct votes (margin=1); a 'fragile wrong' majority has exactly m wrong votes. Filtering utility is nonzero only when the pool contains fragile majorities. The critic removes candidates; a true positive on a wrong candidate in a fragile-wrong pool can flip it right (gain), while a false positive on a correct candidate in a fragile-correct pool can flip it wrong (loss). Net benefit = P(fragile-wrong) * r * flip_success - P(fragile-correct) * (1-p) * flip_failure. Strict benefit requires the first term to exceed the second, yielding the precision threshold above. At k=5, the fragility window is 1/6 < e < 5/7 (approx 0.17 < e < 0.71); the observed hard set at e=0.01 is below this window (no fragile majorities), and the easy set at e=0.033 is also below — explaining zero net benefit in both.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"odd k >= 3\", \"base error e in (1/(k+1), k/(k+2))\", \"critic with precision p above the threshold p > (1-r)*F_broke/(r*F_fixed)\", \"critic recall r > 0\"]}, \"excludes\": [\"e <= 1/(k+1): majorities are robustly correct, filtering cannot help\", \"e >= k/(k+2): majorities are robustly wrong, critic would need near-perfect recall to recover\", \"even k: tie-breaking complicates margin analysis\", \"critic with p below threshold: false flags net-harm\"], \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Experiment arm at e=0.25, k=7, critic p=0.4, r=0.6: fragile-correct outnumber fragile-wrong and low precision causes net harness score < self-consistency score\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment arm at e=0.25, k=7, critic p=0.85, r=0.6: high precision suppresses false flags but recall too low to flip enough fragile-wrong pools, yielding harness score == self-consistency score (no strict gain)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment arm at e=0.05, k=7, critic p=0.9, r=0.9: e below fragility window so few fragile majorities exist, harness score == self-consistency score\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment arm at e=0.25, k=7, critic p=0.75, r=0.8, adaptive-confidence variant: non-adaptive arm shows strict gain but adaptive arm shows no additional gain (adaptive confidence unnecessary in this regime)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This subsumes 7811dbda and 2d711b2e by providing the full precision condition (not just the error window) and explaining the observed zero-net-benefit as a consequence of operating below the fragility window. The decisive experiment should sweep e across {0.12, 0.20, 0.25, 0.35, 0.50} at k=7 with a calibrated critic (p and r measured empirically), testing both sides of the predicted precision threshold. Budget: ~200 questions x 7 candidates x ~300 tokens = 420k generation tokens; critic filtering ~200 x 7 x 100 tokens = 140k; total ~560k, within 300k if questions reduced to 100.\"}", "refs": [{"role": "dependence", "target": "7811dbda8316264703217e333840089b140aa9a640a7f195c385b88c8394d3dc"}, {"role": "dependence", "target": "2d711b2eb5fff4e61cba262914dc9aa29cf142c91d43bf4fffdda495e76c90c4"}, {"role": "dependence", "target": "5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"}, {"role": "mention", "target": "30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"}], "typicality": 0.85}, {"content": "{\"claim\": \"No fixed-precision/recall critic can strictly beat self-consistency across a heterogeneous question set; harness strictly wins only when the critic produces question-adaptive confidence scores c(q) such that the critic filters with a per-question threshold that separates high-error questions (where broken majorities concentrate) from low-error questions (where filtering would only cause false flags), concentrating its recall budget on questions where base error is near 1/(k+1).\", \"mechanism\": \"A fixed critic applies the same precision/recall to all questions. On a heterogeneous set, low-error questions contribute fragile-correct majorities (false-positive risk) while high-error questions contribute fragile-wrong majorities (true-positive opportunity). A fixed critic cannot distinguish these ex ante (it sees candidates, not the true answer), so its false-positive rate on low-error questions cancels or exceeds its true-positive gains on high-error questions. A critic with question-adaptive confidence (e.g., verbalized uncertainty calibrated against per-question candidate disagreement) can set a high bar for filtering on questions where candidates largely agree (low base error) and a low bar where candidates disagree (high base error), thereby avoiding false flags on robust majorities while aggressively filtering fragile ones. The mechanism is selective abstention: the critic must know WHEN not to filter.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"heterogeneous question sets with per-question base error varying across the fragility window\", \"critic with question-adaptive confidence (verbalized or implicit calibration)\", \"any k >= 3\"]}, \"excludes\": [\"homogeneous question sets where all questions share the same base error (fixed-precision critic suffices, per candidate 1)\", \"critic with no question-adaptive signal (e.g., fixed threshold)\"], \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Fixed-precision critic arm at mean e=0.25, k=5, heterogeneous per-question e in [0.05, 0.45]: harness score <= self-consistency score (net zero or negative from false flags on low-e questions)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Question-adaptive critic arm same distribution: harness score strictly > self-consistency score by at least 3 percentage points\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Question-adaptive critic with random confidence shuffle (decoupled from candidate disagreement): harness score <= self-consistency score, showing the adaptivity must be genuinely informative\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Fixed-precision critic on homogeneous e=0.25, k=7, p=0.75, r=0.8: harness strictly beats self-consistency (contradicting the claim that fixed critics never help — this is excluded by scope)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is the direct extension of 30e483eb, which already claimed question-adaptive confidence is necessary. The key addition is the causal mechanism: the critic must use candidate disagreement (or equivalent per-question signal) as a proxy for base error to decide whether to filter. The decisive experiment uses a heterogeneous set of ~120 questions drawn from two difficulty tiers (e~0.10 and e~0.35), compares three arms (self-consistency, fixed-threshold harness, adaptive-threshold harness) at k=7. Budget: 120 x 7 x 300 = 252k generation + 120 x 7 x 150 critic = 126k; total ~378k — trim to 100 questions to fit 300k. The adaptive threshold is set by fitting critic confidence to candidate agreement rate on a held-out 20-question calibration split.\"}", "refs": [{"role": "dependence", "target": "30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"}, {"role": "dependence", "target": "5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"}, {"role": "mention", "target": "7811dbda8316264703217e333840089b140aa9a640a7f195c385b88c8394d3dc"}], "typicality": 0.65}, {"content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic's per-candidate error detection is approximately conditionally independent of the majority outcome given candidate correctness AND the critic operates in the high-leverage regime where P(exactly m correct) is maximized; at low k (k=5) this regime is too narrow to reliably hit, but at k >= 11 the binomial mass on the fragility boundary broadens, making strict gains achievable with even a modestly calibrated critic (precision 0.5-0.7, recall 0.5-0.7).\", \"mechanism\": \"The probability of a fragile majority (exactly m correct out of k) follows Binomial(k, 1-e) at point m. For k=5, m=3, this peaks at e close to 0.4 but the peak is narrow and the absolute probability is moderate (~0.35). For k=11, m=6, the peak is wider and the absolute probability near e=0.45 is higher (~0.22 but the adjacent cells m=5 and m=7 are also substantial, giving a wider effective fragility zone). The key mechanism is that larger k smooths the fragility window: there are more marginal-majority configurations, so the critic has more opportunities to flip outcomes. However, conditional independence of critic errors from majority outcomes is critical: if the critic is systematically more likely to flag candidates in already-correct majorities (e.g., because confident correct answers look 'suspicious'), false flags cluster on fragile-correct pools and net harm results. The critic must be calibrated such that P(flag | wrong, pool majority) ~= P(flag | wrong, pool minority) and P(no-flag | correct, pool majority) ~= P(no-flag | correct, pool minority).\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"k >= 11 (large jury)\", \"base error e in broadened fragility window (1/(k+1), k/(k+2))\", \"critic with approximately conditionally-independent error detection\", \"modest critic calibration (p in [0.5, 0.7], r in [0.5, 0.7])\"]}, \"excludes\": [\"k <= 5: fragility window too narrow for reliable strict gains with modest calibration\", \"critic whose errors are conditionally dependent on majority outcome (e.g., systematically biased toward flagging in correct majorities)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"k=11, e=0.42, critic p=0.55, r=0.55 with verified conditional independence: harness score strictly > self-consistency by >= 2 percentage points\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"k=11, e=0.42, critic p=0.55, r=0.55 but critic flags are conditionally dependent on majority (P(flag|correct, fragile-correct) > 2 * P(flag|correct, fragile-wrong)): harness score < self-consistency score\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"k=5, e=0.40, critic p=0.60, r=0.60: harness score == self-consistency score (insufficient fragility mass at small k for modest calibration)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"k=11, e=0.05, critic p=0.70, r=0.70: e below fragility window, harness score == self-consistency score\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is the most atypical candidate because it challenges the neighborhood's focus on k=5 and argues that the observed failures are partly a small-k artifact. The decisive experiment sweeps k across {5, 7, 11, 15} at a fixed e near the fragility peak (e ~ 0.4 for odd k) with a single modestly-calibrated critic, measuring conditional independence of critic flags via a chi-square test on flag-vs-majority contingency. Budget constraint: k=11 requires 11 candidates/question; at 80 questions x 11 x 200 tokens = 176k generation + 80 x 11 x 150 critic = 132k = 308k. Trim to 75 questions or reduce k sweep to {5, 7, 11} to fit 300k. The conditional independence test is the novel discriminative element: it predicts that even a high-precision critic fails if its errors cluster on correct majorities.\"}", "refs": [{"role": "dependence", "target": "5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"}, {"role": "mention", "target": "7811dbda8316264703217e333840089b140aa9a640a7f195c385b88c8394d3dc"}, {"role": "mention", "target": "74fde5320d6c79520ea82d22a3e0c25a5ecc8e0cb50c3197058c5a3b0ecd2845"}], "typicality": 0.35}]}